\begin_layout Subsection
Iterative Elimination - Hotelling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a finite interval (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

a beach
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) and ice-cream sellers who decide where to reside on that interval.
 Assume people are uniformly distributed across the interval.
 They go to the nearest ice-cream service, then go back to their place and
 eat there.
 The utility from eating the ice-cream depends on the distance (cost of
 walking twice, including the melted ice-cream).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The question is: given this model regarding the people behavior, where do
 we expect the sellers to be located, and what prices will they charge?
 This problem can also be applies to political parties and voters.
 By elimination, we get convergence to the middle point (Black's theorem),
 which states that in political competition, politicians will advocate the
 policy that is preferred by the median voter.
\end_layout

